that hits are uniformly distributed over \code{U}, the count \code{k} of
hits inside the near zone follows \code{Binomial(N, f_d)}. The best \code{d}
per motif is reported, Bonferroni-corrected over the candidate
distances, then BH-adjusted across motifs. Fast, but the
uniform-hit null cannot correct composition bias.}
\item{\code{"permutation"}}{The anchors (not the hits) are randomised
within \code{U} \code{n.perm} times; the binomial z-score is recomputed each
time to build an empirical null. Randomising the anchors keeps the
real hits (and their composition-driven clustering) fixed, so the
test asks whether hits are closer to the real anchors than to
random ones, which absorbs composition and mappability bias. This
is the recommended method when composition bias is a concern.
Uses the global RNG, so call \code{\link[=set.seed]{set.seed()}} beforehand for
reproducible p-values (see \code{nthreads}).}
\item{\code{"ks"}}{A threshold-free one-sided Kolmogorov-Smirnov test of
the per-hit distance-to-nearest-anchor against its analytical null
CDF (\code{f} as a function of \code{d}). P-values are approximate under the
integer-distance ties; \code{"permutation"} is the exact alternative.
Only available for \code{count = "hits"} and
\code{orientation = "undirected"}.}
